title: ‘Get tough on crime’: Jacinta Allan’s crime legislation is ‘imaginary and self-congratulatory’
description: Sky News host James Macpherson examines Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan’s vow to tackle crime in Melbourne, likening her crime legislation to her economic policy; “imaginary and self-congratulatory”.   “Another day in Melbourne, another solemn vow from Premier Jacinta Allan to ‘get tough on crime’,” Mr Macpherson said.  “Apparently, the fifteenth time's the charm.  “Jacinta Allan's tough on crime legislation is like her economic policy – imaginary and self-congratulatory.”

title: ‘Climate leadership’: Green hysteria on show amid COP30 summit
description: Sky News host James Macpherson dissects the COP30 summit, calling out the hypocrisy of the nations and individuals who attended.   “A quick update from COP30 where the only thing more dangerous than the carbon emissions are the lies, the hypocrisy, and the smell of sanctimony so thick it could cause its own greenhouse effect,” Mr Macpherson said.  “When they start taking sailing ships to these conferences, well then, I'll listen. Until then, the only thing hotter than the planet is the sheer volume of hypocrisy burning in Brazil this week.”

title: ‘Remarkably unpopular’: Keir Starmer’s leadership may be challenged
description: Spiked Online Editor Tom Slater says UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer is a “remarkably unpopular prime minister” amid rumours his leadership may be challenged.  “Keir Starmer is a remarkably unpopular prime minister, the most unpopular serving prime minister,” Mr Slater told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “It’s a complete mess; it’s not obvious what all of this briefing was meant to achieve.”

title: ‘Staged’: Liberal Party meeting on net-zero
description: Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell mocks “staged” press footage from the net-zero meeting, which would make “front page” media.  “With them contemplating rolling a female leader, they put three women at the front,” Mr Clennell told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “Including Jacinta Nampijinpa Price, who, of course, is very popular … so that’s quite deliberate.”

title: Vile neo-Nazi rally shocks Sydney, sparks push for tougher hate speech laws
description: Former Labor MP Michael Danby raises concerns over the troubling intersection of extreme left rhetoric and neo-Nazi exploitation in Australia, pushing for tougher laws against hate speech.  “The Iranian intelligence service thinks the atmosphere is so vibrant in Australia that they can blow up synagogues and burn down childcare centres,”  “The Authorities have let things drift.”

title: Ben Shapiro’s outlandish comments telling America’s youth to leave
description: Political Advisor and Commentator CJ Pearson disagrees with The Daily Wire Co-Founder and Host Ben Shapiro after he said young people should just leave America if they can’t afford to live there.   “I think that type of just pessimism is not what's going to be what wins over the hearts and minds of young people,” Mr Pearson told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “The American dream should be attainable if you are American.  “Are you to just lose our best and brightest.”

title: ‘No woman’s land’: Coalition divided on net zero policy
description: Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell criticises Opposition Leader Sussan Ley for doing “whatever it takes” to save her “leadership,” instead of advocating for her supporters.  “Would Sussan Ley have been better off backing net zero and just going down?” Mr Clennell told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “At least be seen to stand for something, and at least stand for your supporters.  “You’re in no woman’s land … she's just trying to save her leadership.”

title: ‘Complete dog's breakfast’: Net zero has divided the Liberal Party
description: Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell says a “leader” would have gone behind the scenes and “fashioned a policy” on emissions reduction targets.  “If she [Sussan Ley] could convince them [moderates], look, we can still tackle emissions reduction, but power prices have to be the main gain,” Mr Clennell told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “Then we would have had a pretty unified front today.  “We didn't, we had a complete dog's breakfast … the division in that party.”

title: Liberals should listen to the ‘referendum’ and drop net-zero
description: Nationals MP Michael McCormack says Liberal members who are backing their net-zero position should talk to farmers, firefighters, and other workers affected by the policy to “change their minds”.  “We live in a democracy where majority rules and majority wins,” Ms McCormack told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “So those Liberals, those moderates, who think that it's a good idea to hang onto this policy ought to visit the referendum.”

title: Democrats ‘cave’ as US government shutdown comes to an end
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada says the US government’s longest shutdown is coming to an end after “41 days,” in which the Democrats had to “cave”.  “It was starting to hurt the everyday person,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “It hurts the government in power; it's just a reminder of the inefficiency and the gridlock that we have in Washington.”

title: Study finds children are ‘financially dependent’ on parents in their adult lives
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond analyses a study by the University of Newcastle, which looked at how Victorian parents are helping their children financially in their retirement.   “It’s uncovered just how far this has gone, the fact that parents are now paying for things for their adult children even further into their lives,” Mr Bond said.   “The biggest thing which came out of this study, which looked at a whole group of families in Victoria … more than half of them … said that they were taking into consideration how they would support their children financially in their retirement.”

title: Merri-bek City Council under fire as ratepayers fund $45,000 pride flag painting
description: Sky News host Freya Leach says Merri-bek City Council is spending $45,000 on a pride painting.   “There is no shortage of councils in this country that are spending money on the most ridiculous things,” Ms Leach said.  “Merri-bek Council down in Victoria is spending $45,000 on a pride painting; they are painting the road with a pride flag.”

title: BBC claims there’s ‘nothing wrong’ with Trump's edited speech
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond mocks Outgoing BBC Director General Tim Davie, who claims there is “nothing wrong at all” with the selectively edited speech of US President Donald Trump.  “He's just blind to what has actually been going on … it's actually everyone else who is at fault,” Mr Bond said.  It [BBC] may thrive, but that’s partly because you are leaving.”

title: ‘Never defined what an Aboriginal is’: Native title claims under fire as groups target MCG
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean analyses the native title claim over Greater Melbourne, claiming Australia has “never defined what an Aboriginal is or should mean”.  “All those people … who correctly warned about where this would end up have been justified,” Mr Dean said.  “We’ve never defined what an Aboriginal is or should mean … we’ve never really defined what traditional ownership means.”

title: ‘Enough is enough’: Liberals to decide on the net-zero ‘debacle’
description: Broadcaster Lucy Zelic is “frustrated” with how long it’s taken for the Liberals to decide on the net-zero “debacle”.  “Make your minds up already, enough is enough,” Ms Zelic told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “Particularly for Sussan Ley, who has been in politics for over two decades.  “We have serious and far bigger problems than what’s already going on with the factionism within this party.”
